T1  - Who knows what when? The information content of pre-IPO market prices
AU  - Löffler, Gunter
AU  - Panther, Patrick F.
AU  - Theissen, Erik
JO  - Journal of Financial Intermediation
VL  - 14
IS  - 4
SP  - 466
EP  - 484
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/10/01/
SN  - 1042-9573
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jfi.2004.06.004
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1042957304000336
KW  - Initial public offerings
KW  - Underpricing
KW  - When-issued trading
KW  - Asymmetric information
KW  - Winner's curse
KW  - Information production
AB  - To resolve the IPO underpricing puzzle it is essential to analyze who knows what when during the issuing process. In Germany, broker-dealers make a market in IPOs that starts as soon as the offer range is published. We examine these pre-IPO prices and find that they are highly informative. They are closer to the first price subsequently established on the exchange than both the midpoint of the offer range and the offer price. The pre-IPO prices explain a large part of the underpricing left unexplained by other variables. The results imply that information asymmetries are much lower than the observed variance of underpricing suggests. They cast doubt on the informational role of bookbuilding and the relevance of the winner's curse problem.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Risk-based capital standards, deposit insurance, and procyclicality
AU  - Pennacchi, George G.
JO  - Journal of Financial Intermediation
VL  - 14
IS  - 4
SP  - 432
EP  - 465
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/10/01/
SN  - 1042-9573
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jfi.2004.09.001
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1042957304000671
AB  - This article shows that risk-based deposit insurance premiums generate smaller procyclical effects than do risk-based capital requirements. Thus, Basel II's procyclical impact can be reduced by integrating risk-based deposit insurance. If deposit insurance is structured as a moving average of contracts, its procyclical effects can be decreased further. Empirical illustrations of this are presented for 42 banks over the period 1987 to 1996. The results confirm that lengthening the contracts' maturities intertemporally smooths premiums but raises the average premium level needed to compensate the insurer for greater systematic risk. The distribution of risk-based premiums across banks is skewed.
